{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"40735872-366a-4002-b651-6bb444894f7e","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the OS automatically generates a `.ips` crash report. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level crashes:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level crashes:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nFiles are named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`.\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them.\n\n**For a core dump** (optional):\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\nThen re-run your app — the core file lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n> **Tip:** The `.ips` file contains the full native backtrace. If you need to symbolicate the .NET runtime frames, I can help with that — just provide the `.ips` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6f65e9f5-cfd0-478d-a63d-2ecc05c44c89","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without createdump available. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search code or run commands. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":286,"requestId":"CB00:392B11:6EF057:7F34AD:6A0529BC"},"id":"81db9122-fe15-415a-8ff9-523533a366ac","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:47:49.448Z","parentId":"4ce0ab38-5384-4d14-93d6-da3f747e9333"}
